Harriſon, alias Johnſon, was a Prieſt, who, for a conſiderable time, hadThis agrees with the Character, that Brice Blair, gives of him, in his Depoſitions. been entruſted with the Management of King James's Affairs. He was a Violent Melfordian; 

   •
an Active and Zealous Agent of the Party, and ſo far from being troubl'd with the Scruples, and Checks of a tender Conſcience; that he never look'd upon any thing as Difficult or Criminal, that might ſerve to promote the Intereſt of the Faction. He had entertain'd a long Correſpondence with Melfort; who loſt his Credit at the Court of St. Germains, upon the miſcarriage of the intended Invaſion; for, as we obſerv'd before, 'twas the conſtant Practice of the Late King's Council, in ſuch Iunctures, to advance Middleton, in Complaiſance to the Proteſtant Jacobites.
